[1] Cholera - Mozambique
Date: Mon 5 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com & Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique (Maputo) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200407050539.html>

Cholera death toll 115
----------------------
The cholera epidemic that struck Mozambique in the first months of 2004
claimed at least 115 victims, according to Health Minister Francisco
Songane, cited in the Mon 5 Jul 2004 issue of the Maputo daily "Noticias."
About 23 000 cases of the disease were diagnosed since this outbreak began
in December 2003. Songane was speaking during a ceremony on Fri 2 Jul 2004
at which Portuguese ambassador Antonio Sennfelt handed over a check for USD
10 000 earmarked for cholera prevention actions in Mozambique.
Songane explained that the number of deaths, most of which were reported in
the cities of Maputo, Beira and Quelimane, corresponds to a lethality rate
of 0.5 percent. Lamenting the situation, he noted, however, that this
lethality rate is below what the World Health Organization (WHO) classifies
as worrying levels. Songane said that, at the moment, the situation is
under control with reports of only between 2 and 3 cases a day
country-wide. But he urged the authorities, and the society at large, to
keep up preventive measures, particularly through improving sanitation
conditions. For his part, Sennfelt said that this money is the contribution
of his government to the fight against the epidemic, particularly in the
central region of the country.
"It is our wish that this money we are granting to the Health Ministry be
used for cholera prevention in Zambezia province, particularly in Quelimane
city," he said. Songane promised that the money will be used for the
intended purpose, and, in the indicated place. He lamented the fact that
cholera is a cyclical epidemic in Mozambique and, again, he insisted that
better sanitation is the solution to the problem.
--
