[3] Diarrhea - Philippines (Pangasinan)
Date: Sun 4 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Sun Star Network Online [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/net/2004/07/04/hospital.reports.12.diar
rheal.deaths.html>

Hospital reports 12 diarrheal deaths
------------------------------------
12 patients died of acute gastroenteritis at the Pangasinan Provincial
Hospital (PPH) in a span of 1 month, hospital authorities said. Dr.
Policarpio Manuel, PPH clinic head, said the number of patients admitted to
the hospital from 1 Jun to 1 Jul 2004 reached 748.
San Carlos has the highest number of victims of gastroenteritis with 458
patients, followed by Malasiqui with 128 victims. The other diarrheal
victims are from Basista, 59; Calasiao, 32; Urbiztondo, 22; Sta. Barbara,
20; Lingayen, 7; Binmaley, 6; Mangaldan and Bayambang, 5 each; Bugallon,
3; Mapandan, Aguilar and Labrador, 1 each. Of the fatalities, San Carlos
and Malasiqui have 3 each as of 26 Jun 2004. The Region I Medical Center
also recorded 2 deaths due to gastroenteritis. The casualties were from
Mangaldan town.
The PPH official said there that is no update yet of what had been said
about the result of the swab examination of 9 patients from Malasiqui. 6 of
them had been found to be afflicted with cholera. "As of now, there are no
other figure[s] concerning cholera," he said.
Manuel further disclosed that 90 percent of the patients discharged from
the PPH have fully recovered, except for 10 percent who went out voluntarily
without having fully recovered. "It is the risk of the patients, and their
local officials will be responsible for following them up," he said.
He also said that, in his talk with sanitary engineers and inspectors,
it was discovered that, in the gastroenteritis-affected areas, septic tanks
of the households are less than 10 meters away from deep artesian wells.
"There is a great possibility that the water pump could have been [sucking]
bacteria from the septic tank. So we advise that they should not get their
drinking water there," he said. But Manuel said that if they do not have
other sources of water, then they should boil the water for 5 to 10 minutes.
[Byline: Fred P. Macaraeg]
[ProMED has previously reported in Cholera, diarrhea & dysentery update
2004 (14) 20040628.1726 on documented cases of cholera and amoebic dysentery
from this area. - Mod.LL]
